data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that must be replaced:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop` while loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Preventing rethrow so `finally` runs | Remove — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` "may block" | Pass `CancellationToken` to unblock it |

### Why `Thread.Abort` fails on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime — the CLR no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into another thread. You **must** switch to cooperative cancellation where the worker code voluntarily checks for and responds to a cancellation request.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — OperationCanceledException does not
                // auto-rethrow, so the finally block runs normally and the
                // loop condition exits naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the worker to finish (replaces the Sleep + Abort pattern)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### What must change in `GetNextItem`

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." **This is the critical part** — if it blocks indefinitely, cancellation will stall because cooperative cancellation only works if the code checks the token. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// If it uses a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If it uses a ManualResetEvent or similar wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it calls Thread.Sleep:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollIntervalMs); // replaces Thread.Sleep
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return TryDequeue();
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | If it blocks on I/O or a wait handle without a token, `Cancel()` has no effect and `Join` will time out — your old `Thread.Abort` fallback is gone. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable`; leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Implement `IDisposable` on the host class. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from unrelated exceptions. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` does long CPU work, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it at regular intervals. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in the old `Stop()`** | Replaced by `Join(timeout)` which actually waits for the thread to finish rather than hoping it's done after an arbitrary delay. |
